Under the hood, assertEquals(..., ...) is basically just this:
if (!expect.equals(actual)) {
    throw new AssertionError(providedMessage);
}

So, so long as your objects have a sensible equals() implementation (they do!), you can make high-level assertions on objects using jUnit's assertEquals(...) methods.
Here, what I propose is to reword this into one bit assertion statement, like:
assertEquals(
    /* expected */ new GraphQLResponse(
        null,
        Arrays.asList(
            new GraphQLError("Confict resolver rejects ...", ,, ) // build these up, from the fields in your assertions
        )
    ),
    actualResponse /* built the same exact way you are now, in the Act portion. */
);

